notes:
Remix album released in 1995.
Compared to the single CD version, "The Updates" contains an extra remix by Oliver Lieb, different remixes by The Grid and Plutone, and longer versions of the remixes by Westbam, Jens, Jam & Spoon, Ilsa Gold, Carl Cox and The Orb.
The vinyl box set contains the exclusive "Vicious Games (Instrumental Acid)" remix by The Grid.

Associated singles:
[m37888]
[m37956]
[m3264421]

As there were three different The Grid remixes of "Vicious Games", spread over the different formats of "Hands on Yello", there were possibly plans to release a "The Grid's Hands On Yello – Vicious Games" single.

notes:
This single was one of Enigma's four singles from its second album, [m=85867]. The video for this song was recorded in the rural areas of Nepal.
Similar with "[m=85870]", the song featured samples of Mongolian Folk Music and samples taken from the album [m117420].
It also contains samples from [a6520]'s song "[r=637067]", [m30008]", NASA retransmissions sampled from "Mare Tranquillitatis" performed by [a7027], and [a124506]' "Dreaming While You Sleep".

name: Cerrone 3 (Supernature)
songs: Supernature|Sweet Drums|In The Smoke|Give Me Love|Love Is Here|Love Is The Answer
notes:
On Supernature, Mark used for the first time an ARP Odyssey at Trident Studio in London. The song features an environmental theme, imagining a future where the use of artificial chemicals in agriculture has caused "creatures down below" to emerge and "take their sweet revenge" against mankind. The lyrics were written by producer [a218098] and [a107070] (although official credited first on the [r=151560] remix) and was inspired by the SF novel The Island of Dr. Moreau by H. G. Wells.
In 1987 Lena Lovich did her version on the compilation [m=48723]

name: Deep Inside
songs: Deep Inside|No Cure|Just Believe|Maurice's Vibe|Deep Inside (The Dub)
notes:
Master for Hard(d)rive EP and remixes of its lead track, "Deep Inside".

Little Louie Vega originally made a 5-track EP for Strictly Rhythm under the alias Hardrive (sometimes misspelt as Harddrive). This EP contains two versions of "Deep Inside" plus the tracks "No Cure", "Maurice's Vibe" and "Just Believe". The EP was released in various territories outside the US as well.
"Deep Inside" became the most popular track of the EP and was remixed in Italy by Alex Party shortly thereafter. These remixes were released as UMM 117 and can be found in this master.

New Masters At Work remixes of "Deep Inside" were made in 1995, along with a new recording, "Is It What We Need?". These remixes (SR 12399) can also be found in this master.
At the same time, Strictly Rhythm released the Hardrive EP on CD, featuring the original 5 tracks, one of the new remixes and "Is It What We Need".

"Deep Inside" was remixed in 2009 once more.

Do not use this master for the remix of "Just Believe": [m1250311].

"No Cure" contains elements of "Love Hangover" by Diana Ross.

Co-vocals are performed by Nikki, which is confirmed by herself ([a=Nicole Yarling]), a previous member of [a=U96].

name: Heaven
songs: Heaven|Are You Ready? (Space Symphony)|A Night To Remember|Venus In Chains|Drag Queen|Try|Love Generation|1-900-Love|Heartline/ Lifeline|Life In Paradise|Anthem
notes: In 1996 the fourth U96 album, Heaven was released. The album was highly commercial in sound, with greater emphasis on Eurodance, despite retaining some electro and trance influences. On this album a new singer Dea-Li (Dorothy Lapi) was featured, who participated in the preparation of four titles. The refrain in the song Heaven - although with a higher pace and different text - closely resembles Cyndi Lauper's 1984 hit song Time After Time. The second single A Night To Remember was a Top-20 Hit in Austria and Finland. The final single Venus In Chains peaked at number 7 in the Czech Republic.

name: Everything Starts With An "E"
songs: Everything Begins With An 'E'|Everything Begins With An 'E' (Instrumental)|Everything Begins With An 'E' (Beats)
notes:
Contains a re-interpretation of "Robinson Crusoe Suite" (1964 TV Series Theme)


A plethora of different matrix and label combinations of the first UK edition with catalogue number PROT 1-12 exist.

On one set of labels the tracks are correctly called "Everything S̲t̲a̲r̲t̲s̲ With An 'E'". These labels also have the durations printed on them.
On another set of labels the tracks are incorrectly called "Everything B̲e̲g̲i̲n̲s̲ With An 'E'". These labels have no durations printed on them.

Some releases have a mixture of these labels.

Both sets of labels have the same tracks printed on them but in many cases the vinyl actually plays different mixes than what is printed on the labels.

The following matrixes exist for UK releases with the catalogue number PROT 1-12:
M1: A̶L̶ ̶5̶A̶ ̶-̶1̶U̶-̶1̶-̶1̶ PROT 112 A-1U-1-1 D
Plays the original unnamed mix.

M2: A̶L̶ ̶5̶B̶ ̶-̶1̶U̶-̶1̶-̶1̶ PROT 112 B-1U-1-1 D
Plays the Instrumental mix and the Beats mix.

M3: PROT 112 A-2U-1-1
Also containes the hand etched message “Ronald McDonald Cow Killer”
Plays the Sir Fredrick Leighton Remix.

M4: PROT 112 B-2U-1-1
Plays the Kinky Transformer mix.

The following labels and matrix combinations currently exist in the DB:

[url=http://www.discogs.com/release/56174]Begins-A / Begins-B / M1 / M2[/url]
[url=http://www.discogs.com/release/5382583]Begins-A / Starts-B / M1 / M4[/url]
[url=http://www.discogs.com/release/1351400]Begins-A / Begins-B / M1 / M4[/url]
[url=http://www.discogs.com/release/556438]Starts-A / Starts-B / M1 / M4[/url]
[url=http://www.discogs.com/release/3762691]Begins-A / Begins-B / M3 / M4[/url]
[url=http://www.discogs.com/release/5616013]Begins-A / Begins-B / M3 / M2[/url]

There is also confirmed that a variation with Starts-A / Begins-B / M1 / M4 exist but at the time of writing it haven’t been submitted to the DB yet.


The different mixes can be identified by the following characteristics:
The original mix is about 7:10 long and starts with an electric guitar solo
The Sir Fredrick Leighton Remix is about 7:49 and starts with the Ronald McDonald sample "Everything Starts With An E"
The Kinky Transformer Mix has a sample at the beginning saying "Do You Wanna Dance" and is 5:01 long
The instrumental mix is, well, mostly instrumental. Just beats at the beginning and it's about 5:21 long
The Beats mix is basically the same as the original mix with about 20 seconds edited away from the middle of the track.

name: U
songs: U (V-Mix)|U (U-Mix)|U (W-Mix)|U (X-Mix)
notes:
The "I've got a feeling..." vocal sample was taken from the Todd Terry 'House Of Todd' remix of 'Little Bird' by Annie Lennox. Although it appears on the 'De Zenk' and 'FVV' mixes from 'U: The Feeling Mixes' (dose 018r) on the Overdose label, the Positiva label subsequently had Stacy Seldon re-make the sample on copyright grounds. According to Frank Zenker, in an [url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qaFwqW5LKb0]interview[/url], Positiva felt that there would be zero chance of clearing the original sample - which suggests that Overdose might have released it without clearance.

Some mixes of the track ('V' and 'De Zenk') also sample the very distinctive drum-loop from the Perplexer remix of [m=108964]. Frank also explained how his failure to clear this sample (before copies were released) nearly landed him serious legal trouble, until a deal was worked out.

notes:
Released to promote "The Best Of Tanita Tikaram". 12" features mixes by Baby Bumps, Phil Kelsey and Ramp. CD adds another Baby Bumps mix. Three more mix variants appeared on promo 2×12". 'Tikaramp Radio' appears on "The Best Of", other mixes are exclusive to this single.
Tikaram herself didn't think the track would benefit from remixing and wasn't happy with the result, which was released without her authority.

The original [url=http://www.discogs.com/master/41851]"Twist In My Sobriety"[/url] was released in 1988.

Various different mixes released over time on different editions.

KLF 005T was initially due to be released 31 Oct 1988, and then for 12 Dec 1988 (according to Music Week), but ultimately was delayed until well into 1989.

songs: Now That We Found Love ("Remix By David Meyer")|Elevate My Mind ("Remix By David Meyer")|Classic Remix|Radio Activity ("Remix By Fabian Pulido")|Summertime ("Remix By David Meyer")|3 A.M. Eternal ("Remix By Two White Guys Mixing")|Wicked Beat 15|Wicked Beat 16|Samples & Scratches

name: The White Room
songs: What Time Is Love? (LP Mix)|Make It Rain|3 A.M. Eternal (Live At The S.S.L.)|Church Of The KLF|Last Train To Trancentral (LP Mix)|Build A Fire|The White Room|No More Tears|Justified And Ancient
notes:
The US version of 'The White Room' was strongly edited for its official commercial release.
It has a total playing time of 39:39, and it contains 9 tracks.

The original UK version presents the first five tracks ('What Time Is Love?' through 'Last Train To Trancentral') as a kind of 'mini-concert' with sampled crowd noise from, among other places, U2's 'Rattle And Hum'. All five tracks are segued and mixed.
It has a total playing time printed of 45:05, but in reality it's only 43:54. It lists 9 songs, but only has 8 indexed.

The US version eliminates the crowd noise, with some tracks fading out near the end. This is probably as the crowd noise was sampled from a Doors album and hence the obvious copyright problems.
It also has the single mix of 'Last Train To Trancentral' instead of the mellower UK album version, edits 'No More Tears' down from 9:24 to 6:42, and adds a little more wind noise at the end of the closing 'Justified And Ancient'.

The Japanese version follows the US format, with the single version of 'Last Train To Trancentral' replaced by the 12" version of that mix. In addition, it includes three extra tracks.

On 23rd April 2021 the 'Director's Cut' of the album was made available through streaming services and was the first time the original 1989 cut of the record had been officially released.

This KLF song, alluding to one of their previous aliases, [a21753], comes in 5 main versions, featuring different vocalists:
• Stand By The JAMS, featuring lead vocals by Miss [a16406], The First Lady Of Country
• All Bound For Mu Mu Land and Make Mine A "99", featuring lead vocals by [a16408]
• The White Room Version, featuring vocals by [a16407]
• Let Them Eat Ice Cream, essentially an instrumental version
All versions except The White Room Version also feature rap by [a28953].

The melody and part of the lyrics of the song first appeared as part of Hey Hey We Are Not The Monkees from The JAMs' debut album, [m=63566]

The 12" was called "Bang (Mind Warp Mutations)" and the compact disc version (with four live tracks) was called "Blur-Ti-Go". These were released to coincide with the group's live tour of the country, and the band notoriously hated them.

notes:
First released in the US in May 1988 by [l=D.J. International Records].
"Forceful underground/house with a message and nice vocal."

Being one of D.J. International's best selling 12"s, the US release has several variants:
- 4LW with dot, no TOP, PAN below spindle hole, Anthony Thomas not underlined, single narrow pressing ring.
- 4LW with dot, no TOP, PAN below spindle hole, Anthony Thomas not underlined, single wide pressing ring.
- 4LW with dot, no TOP, PAN below spindle hole, Anthony Thomas not underlined, dipped labels.
- 4LW with dot, no TOP, PAN below spindle hole, Anthony Thomas [u]underlined[/u], single wide pressing ring.
- 4LW with dot, 2x TOP, PAN [u]above[/u] spindle hole, Anthony Thomas not underlined, single wide pressing ring.
- 4LW [u]without[/u] dot, 2x TOP, PAN [u]above[/u] spindle hole, Anthony Thomas not underlined, dipped labels.
- 4LW [u]without[/u] dot, no TOP, PAN below spindle hole, Anthony Thomas not underlined, dipped labels.
- 4LW [u]without[/u] dot, no TOP, PAN below spindle hole, Anthony Thomas [u]underlined[/u], dipped labels.

Also the internationally licensed releases in the UK and Germany come in different variants. All of them were first released in 1989.

name: Sons Of The P
songs: The DFLO Shuttle|Heartbeat Props|No Nose Job|Sons Of The P|Flowin' On The D-Line|Kiss You Back|Tales Of The Funky|The Higher Heights Of Spirituality|Family Of The Underground|The D-Flowstrumental|Good Thing We're Rappin'
notes: The second full length album from Digital Underground, released in 1991, was even an even further journey into the P. Funk-influenced sounds of Parliament and Funkadelic. This time, George Clinton appears not only in sample form throughout the release, but guests on the title track. The topics on the album ranged from giving respect to still-living black leaders ("Heartbeat Props") to the evils of plastic surgery and the effect of Hollywood on the self-image of young girls ("No Nose Job"), a quasi-fictional tale of pimping ("Good Thing We're Rappin'"), to more imaginative description of the fantastical D.U. universe ("The DFLO Shuttle", "Sons Of The P", "Flowin' On The D-Line").

name: Blade Runner - Esper 'Retirement' Edition (25th Anniversary Culmination)
songs: Main Titles|Blush Response|Wait For Me|Rachel's Song|Love Theme|One More Kiss, Dear|Blade Runner Blues|Memories Of Green|Tales Of The Future|Damask Rose|Blade Runner (End Titles)|Tears In Rain
notes:
The 1994 release was the first official soundtrack album to contain the original recordings as heard in the 1982 film. Several had samples from the film added, and many were specially segued into seamless suites for this release. The contents can be summarized as follows:

• Main Titles [+ film dialogue & sound] / Blush Response [+ film dialogue] / Wait for Me [+ film dialogue] / Rachel's Song*
• Love Theme
• One More Kiss, Dear
• Blade Runner Blues
• Memories of Green** / Tales of the Future* / Damask Rose* / Blade Runner (End Titles) / Tears in Rain [+ film dialogue & sound]

* Composed for the film, but not used in it.
** Used in the film, but not composed for it; originally from the 1980 album [m=6094].

In 1989, several unsegued tracks were released on Vangelis's [m=12258] compilation:

• End Titles [fades out slightly early]
• Love Theme [has a tape speed problem at the start]
• Memories of Green

The only other official soundtrack album release with Vangelis's recordings was the Blade Runner Trilogy 25th Anniversary edition, released in 2007. This 3-CD set included the 1994 album, a disc of 12 previously unreleased tracks, and a disc of 12 new songs inspired by the film.

Meanwhile, over the years, fans compiled a number of bootleg releases, including the comprehensive, well-received "Esper" Editions.

notes:
See also: [m=252887] (has "I'll House You" B-side) and [m=985220].

Versions of "I'll House You" from 1988:
• Club Mix = album version
• I'll Show You / Show Mix / Slow Mix = P.A. backing track
• Housepella / Housapella / Houseapella / A House Is Not A Hut = acapella (mostly)
• The Gee St. Reconstruction [12" version] = remix by Richie Rich. Some reissues omit "Too black, too strong" intro.
• The Gee St. Reconstruction [7" version] / U.K. Remix (7" Edit) = remix edit by Richie Rich.
• Instrumental = instrumental remix by Richie Rich.

Sometimes the titles of the 7" & 12" remix versions are swapped in error.

name: Sunday Girl
songs: Sunday Girl|I Know But I Don't Know
notes:
The master list of the 1978/79/81 releases of the 7" single Sunday Girl as the 'A' side have four different "b" sides:

* Sunday Girl (French Version)
* I Know But I Don't Know
* I'm Gonna Love You Too
* One Way or Another

Some editions have the French version as the "A" side and the English version as the "B" side.  At least one edition has an edit with both languages combined as the "A" side (some lyrics are in English and some in French).

The 12" editions listed here all have Sunday Girl as the "A" side.   Where the same titles appear in a different sequence (so with a different "A" side), they can be found in the master list for that "A" side (e.g. Hanging on The Telephone).

Sunday Girl appears as a "b" side to some singles. The list below is the editions where the track is the "A" side.

The "Search" function will assist easy location of all editions that the title appears on a single.


The track list below only refers to some editions.

notes:
The debut album from Digital Underground.
The cassette version of the album featured three additional songs not available on the CD or LP formats: "Hip Hop Doll," "The Sound Of The Underground," and "A Tribute To The Early Days."  It also contains the full length version of "Gutfest '89," which appeared only in edited form on the CD and LP formats.

songs: Same Song|Tie The Knot|The Way We Swing (Remix)|Nuttin' Nis Funky|Packet Man (Worth A Packet Remix)|Arguin' On The Funk
notes:
An EP release issued in 1991 between the first and second Digital Underground albums, featuring a few new songs, a few remix/reinterpretations off the first album. Two of these new songs were taken from the movie "Nothing But Trouble" (when the EP was released, the movie was still going by its working title, "Valkenvania"; it was renamed "Nothing But Trouble" prior to being released to theaters.)

This EP is noteworthy for featuring the first recorded vocal from Tupac Shakur on the track "Same Song".

name: Sons Of The P
songs: The DFLO Shuttle|Heartbeat Props|No Nose Job|Sons Of The P|Flowin' On The D-Line|Kiss You Back|Tales Of The Funky|The Higher Heights Of Spirituality|Family Of The Underground|The D-Flowstrumental|Good Thing We're Rappin'
notes: The second full length album from Digital Underground, released in 1991, was even an even further journey into the P. Funk-influenced sounds of Parliament and Funkadelic. This time, George Clinton appears not only in sample form throughout the release, but guests on the title track. The topics on the album ranged from giving respect to still-living black leaders ("Heartbeat Props") to the evils of plastic surgery and the effect of Hollywood on the self-image of young girls ("No Nose Job"), a quasi-fictional tale of pimping ("Good Thing We're Rappin'"), to more imaginative description of the fantastical D.U. universe ("The DFLO Shuttle", "Sons Of The P", "Flowin' On The D-Line").
